{
  "doc_id": "19334",
  "text": "Matrix models mostly exhibited a precautionary tendency (i.e. over-estimation) when estimating percent decline. While our observed over-estimation tendency is similar to that presented for scalar models in Dunham et al. [CITATION_1] , we also observed the same patterns in underand over-estimation for \"estimated\" matrix models. A similar construction of matrix models from \"observed\" data was absent from Dunham et al. [CITATION_2] and hence they concluded matrix models are less conservative than scalar models. Dunham et al. [CITATION_3] focused on quasi-extinction risk rather than percent decline; these two metrics may not exhibit exact similarities in their sensitivities to measurement and process error. However, our results do concur with others that have found an over-estimation tendency of extreme decline among PVA methods [CITATION_4] as well as those that suggest that simple models can perform very well relative to matrix models for population projections, especially when uncertainty is high [CITATION_5] .",
